class Solution {
public:
    int maximumLength(string s) {
        int count[26] = {0}; // count[i] stores the count of character i
        int max_length = 0; // stores the maximum length found

        for (char c : s) {
            count[c - 'a']++; // increment count of character c
            if (count[c - 'a'] >= 3) {
                max_length = max(max_length, count[c - 'a'] - 2); // update max_length if a character occurs thrice or more
                count[c - 'a']--; // decrement count of character c
            }
        }

        return max_length;
    }
};
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n) (where n is the length of the string)
space complexity: O(1) (constant space complexity)
energy implications: LOW

Explanation:

We use a 26-element array to store the count of each character in the string. We iterate through the string and update the count of characters that occur thrice or more. If a character occurs thrice or more, we update the maximum length found. After processing the entire string, we return the maximum length found. This solution has a time complexity of O(n) because we iterate through the string once. The space complexity is O(1) because we only use a constant amount of space for the array. The energy implications are low because the algorithm only performs a single pass through the string and uses minimal resources.

